snippet.textDisplay: The metaphorical lyrics of this beautiful love duet is simply world-class.  One should take lesson from Bangla literature about how to convey a suggestive message so eloquently through the use of metaphors and figures of speech.  The female lover with desires coinciding with her fertility cycles ("Baro Mash" e "Baro Ful re") is enamoured by this "Nagor" whose looks are nothing short of the beauty possessed by the moon.  But she is unsure about committing to him as he is a traveller ("Kon ba desh e thake bhomra, kon bagan e boshe...") and may not ultimately show up to their love meet.  This is why the male lover enthralled by the scent of her youth or "blooming flower" says in protest "Don't speak to me if you don't show yourself."  Understanding this delicate poem/song about two conversing lovers makes one very proud and appreciative of our Bangla language and its vast depth. Hats off to the singers and composers for this wonderful presentation.
